description: Granodiorite, quartz monzonite, and granite—Light gray to pink, generally weakly foliated. Occur as late syn- to post-tectonic plutons that may be correlative with those dated at 2,699-2,701 Ma in the Kakagi Lake area north of the Sabaskong Batholithic Suite and (or) those about 2,682 Ma to the east in the Rainy Lake area (Davis and others, 1982, 1989; Davis and Edwards, 1986; Goldich and Fisher, 1986)
label: Granodiorite, quartz monzonite, and granite

description: Schist-rich migmatite—Predominantly biotite schist paleosome (unit Wmsb and possibly unit Wmsa of Day and others, 1990) containing interlayers of granitic neosome. Proportion of biotite schist paleosome ranges from 25 to 75 percent. Granitic neosome made up of pink granite (Lac La Croix Granite; Southwick and Sims, 1980), white leucogranite having a gneissic to pegmatitic texture, and light-gray biotite tonalite. Complex small-scale folds are common. Correlates with unit Asm of Jirsa and Boerboom (1990)
label: Schist-rich migmatite

Mafic and felsic metavolcanic rocks—Interlayered metamorphosed bimodal volcanic (basalt, dacite, and rhyolite) flows and tuffs, and minor graywacke and graphitic schists; andesitic volcanic rocks not observed. Sulfide-rich zones (pyrrhotite+pyrite and trace chalcopyrite and sphalerite) present locally interlayered with metavolcanic rocks. Extreme lithologic variability of unit precludes further subdivision. Bimodal volcanism is bracketed between 2,725±2 Ma and 2,728±4/=3 Ma to the east in the Rainy Lake area (Davis and others, 1989).

Mafic metavolcanic rocks—Predominantly dark-green, foliated basalt flows, pillow lava, and mafic tuff. Subordinate interlayers of felsic to intermediate metavolcanic rocks. Gabbro sill intruded, into the lowermost Kattimiaganak Volcanic Group (Late Archean) in the Kakagi Lake area adjacent to the Sabaskong Batholith Suite dated at 2,731±4.0/=2.9 Ma. Recrystallized locally to quartz-amphibolite facies.
Mafic intrusive rock—Dark-green, coarse-grained, moderately foliated to well-foliated metamorphosed gabbro, leucogabbro, norite, and diorite.

Granitoid rocks—Moderately foliated to well-foliated tonalite, granodiorite, granite, and minor quartzodiorite. Includes units Wgmz and Wmz in areas mantled by Quaternary deposits. Early tonalite gneiss of the Sabaskong Batholitihic Suite dated at 2,723±18 Ma by Davis and Edwards (1986). Lithotype dated locally in the Rainy Lake area to the east of the map area at about 2,729–2,736 Ma (Davis and others, 1982; Davis and others, 1989; Goldich and Fischer, 1986).
Ultramafic to mafic intrusive rocks—Peridotite, pyroxenite, serpentinite, gabbro, and leucogabbro; contains serpentine of supracrustal rocks and minor felsic intrusive rocks.

Metasedimentary and metavolcanic rocks—Primarily metamorphosed argillite, chert and chert-breccia, pyritic and graphitic mudstone, sulfide-rich zones, and volcaniclastic sedimentary rocks interlayered with felsic and minor mafic volcanic rocks; associated with unit Wifb. Unit observed solely in drill core; boundaries defined by aeromagnetic expression.
Mafic to intermediate metavolcanic rocks, undivided—Mixed basaltic, andesitic, and minor dacitic metavolcanic rocks.

Iron-formation—Chert and chert-magnetite iron-formation interlayered with subordinate amounts of felsic and mafic volcaniclastic metasedimentary rock. Unit is commonly interlayered with other supra-crustal rock units.

Hornblende monzonite—Dark-green to black monzonite, monzodiorite, and diorite. Defined by aeromagnetic patterns similar to monzonite intrusions mapped along the Pipestone River to the east (Percival and others, 1985).

Metasedimentary rocks, amphibolite facies—Differs from unit Wms in that it is metamorphosed to higher grade (garnet-biotite schist) and may be an allochthonous block correlative with Wmsb southwest of the Rainy Lake–Seine River fault.

Supracrustal rocks—Predominantly dark-gray to brown fine- to medium-grained metagraywacke and slate (biotite schist and pelite). Locally contains minor interlayers of volcanic rocks. Graded bedding locally preserved. Includes Couchiching Group, bracketed between 2,692±2 Ma and 2,704±3 Ma by Davis and others (1989).

Felsic metavolcanic and volcaniclastic metasedimentary rocks—Metasedimentary chert and dacite to rhyolite tuff and flows interlayered with minor volcaniclastic sedimentary rocks, metagrawacke, and iron formation.

Intermediate metavolcanic rocks—Predominantly andesitic to dacitic flows, pillow lava, tuff, and agglomerate; locally interlayered with graywacke.

Chert-rich iron-formation—Chert-hematite iron-formation (± magnetite and (or) limonite) and chert breccia interlayered with argillite, graphitic and pyritic mudstone, felsic metavolcanic and volcaniclastic sediment and minor mafic volcanic rocks. Chert breccia is characterized by variegated brick-red, green, and gray chert clasts in iron oxide(s) matrix; unit interlayered with unit Wmsv.

Granodiorite gneiss—Medium-grained hornblende biotite granodiorite gneiss. Locally contains garnet. Relatively oldest granitoid unit recognized in map area; locally forms inclusions in unit Wmz (SW1/4SW1/4 sec. 7, T. 163 N., R. 33 W.) and is cut by dikes of unit Wg (SE1/4SW1/4 sec. 1, T. 163 N., R. 34 W.).

Schist-rich migmatite—Predominantly biotite schist paleosome (unit Wrnsb) possibly unit Wmsa of Day and others, 1990) containing interlayers of granitic neosome. Proportion of biotite schist paleosome ranges from 25 to 75 percent. Granitic neosome made up of pink granite (Lac La Croix Granite; Southwick and Sims, 1980), white leucogranite having a gneissic to pegmatitic texture, and light-gray biotite tonalite. Complex small-scale folds are common. Correlates with unit Asm of Jirsa and Boerboom (1990).
